interfaces.label: BulkUpdateTaskResult
description: return type of TaskScheduling.bulkUpdateSchedules method

children.label: tasks
description: list of successfully updated tasks

children.label: errors
description: list of failed tasks and errors caused failure

interfaces.label: ConcreteTaskInstance
description: A task instance that has an id and is ready for storage.

children.label: id
description:
The id of the Elastic document that stores this instance's data. This can
be passed by the caller when scheduling the task.

children.label: version
description: The saved object version from the Elasticsearch document.

children.label: scheduledAt
description:
The date and time that this task was originally scheduled. This is used
for convenience to task run functions, and for troubleshooting.

children.label: attempts
description:
The number of unsuccessful attempts since the last successful run. This
will be zeroed out after a successful run.

children.label: status
description: Indicates whether or not the task is currently running.

children.label: runAt
description:
The date and time that this task is scheduled to be run. It is not guaranteed
to run at this time, but it is guaranteed not to run earlier than this.

children.label: startedAt
description:
The date and time that this task started execution. This is used to determine
the "real" runAt that ended up running the task. This value is only set
when status is set to "running".

children.label: retryAt
description:
The date and time that this task should re-execute if stuck in "running" / timeout
status. This value is only set when status is set to "running".

children.label: state
ownerId
description: The random uuid of the Kibana instance which claimed ownership of the task last

children.label: interval
description: An interval in minutes (e.g. '5m'). If specified, this is a recurring task.

interfaces.label: RunContext
description: The run context is passed into a task's run function as its sole argument.

children.label: taskInstance
description: The document describing the task instance, its params, state, id, etc.

children.label: fakeRequest
description:
If an API key is associated with the task, a fake KibanaRequest object
is generated using the API key and passed as part of the run context.

children.label: id
description:
Optional ID that can be passed by the caller. When ID is undefined, ES
will auto-generate a unique id. Otherwise, ID will be used to either
create a new document, or update existing document

children.label: taskType
description: The task definition type whose run function will execute this instance.

children.label: scheduledAt
description:
The date and time that this task was originally scheduled. This is used
for convenience to task run functions, and for troubleshooting.

children.label: startedAt
description:
The date and time that this task started execution. This is used to determine
the "real" runAt that ended up running the task. This value is only set
when status is set to "running".

children.label: retryAt
description:
The date and time that this task should re-execute if stuck in "running" / timeout
status. This value is only set when status is set to "running".

children.label: runAt
description:
The date and time that this task is scheduled to be run. It is not
guaranteed to run at this time, but it is guaranteed not to run earlier
than this. Defaults to immediately.

children.label: schedule
description:
A TaskSchedule string, which specifies this as a recurring task.

Currently, this supports a single format: an interval in minutes or seconds (e.g. '5m', '30s').

children.label: params
description:
A task-specific set of parameters, used by the task's run function to tailor
its work. This is generally user-input, such as { sms: '333-444-2222' }.

children.label: state
traceparent
description: The serialized traceparent string of the current APM transaction or span.

children.label: user
description: The id of the user who scheduled this task.

children.label: scope
description:
Used to group tasks for querying. So, reporting might schedule tasks with a scope of 'reporting',
and then query such tasks to provide a glimpse at only reporting tasks, rather than at all tasks.

children.label: ownerId
description: The random uuid of the Kibana instance which claimed ownership of the task last

children.label: enabled
description: Indicates whether the task is currently enabled. Disabled tasks will not be claimed.

children.label: apiKey
description: Used to allow tasks to be scoped to a user via their API key

children.label: userScope
description: Meta data related to the API key associated with this task

interfaces.label: TaskRegisterDefinition
description:
Defines a task which can be scheduled and run by the Kibana
task manager.

children.label: title
description: A brief, human-friendly title for this task.

children.label: timeout
description:
How long, in minutes or seconds, the system should wait for the task to complete
before it is considered to be timed out. (e.g. '5m', the default). If
the task takes longer than this, Kibana will send it a kill command and
the task will be re-attempted.

children.label: priority
description:
An optional definition of task priority. Tasks will be sorted by priority prior to claiming
so high priority tasks will always be claimed before normal priority, which will always be
claimed before low priority

children.label: cost
description: An optional definition of the cost associated with running the task.

children.label: description
description: An optional more detailed description of what this task does.

children.label: createTaskRunner
description:
Creates an object that has a run function which performs the task's work,
and an optional cancel function which cancels the task.

children.label: maxAttempts
description:
Up to how many times the task should retry when it fails to run. This will
default to the global variable. The default value, if not specified, is 1.

children.label: maxConcurrency
description:
The maximum number tasks of this type that can be run concurrently per Kibana instance.
Setting this value will force Task Manager to poll for this task type separately from other task types
which can add significant load to the ES cluster, so please use this configuration only when absolutely necessary.
The default value, if not given, is 0.
